<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRADLEY'S LAWYERS FOCUS ON ROLE OF S&amp;L IN INVESTMENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GLENN F. BUNTING and RICH CONNELL, Times Staff Writers 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As Mayor Tom Bradley's lawyers sort through his tangled financial records, they 
are attempting to determine what role Columbia Savings &amp; Loan Assn. and its 
vice chairman, Abraham Spiegel, may have played in the mayor's personal 
investment activities, The Times has learned. 
</P>
<P>
A source close to the mayor said Spiegel's office served as a conduit of 
information between Bradley and one of his stockbrokers. Another source 
identified the brokerage firm as Shearson Lehman Hutton. 
</P>
<P>
As recently as January, 1987, Spiegel's office corresponded with Bradley 
concerning the mayor's investment portfolio, the source close to the mayor 
said. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Suggests Possible Advice 
</P>
<P>
This suggests that Spiegel may have provided Bradley with advice on personal 
investments just as his son, Columbia Chairman Thomas Spiegel, has acknowledged 
advising Assistant House Majority Leader Tony Coelho (D-Merced). Thomas Spiegel 
has said he recommended and helped finance an unusual purchase for Coelho of a 
$100,000 "junk bond" issued by Drexel Burnham Lambert. 
</P>
<P>
The Beverly Hills savings and loan and its top officers are being investigated 
in connection with Drexel's indicted junk bond king, Michael Milken. 
</P>
<P>
The Times reported Thursday that records of Bradley's investments with Drexel 
have been subpoenaed by the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan. The demand for 
the records is believed to be part of a broader inquiry by prosecutors into 
Drexel's relations with several politicians. 
</P>
<P>
Columbia and Thomas Spiegel are under investigation by the U.S. attorney's 
office in Manhattan in connection with the allegedly illegal activities of 
Milken and Drexel. Thomas Spiegel said in an interview this week that he 
offered investment advice to a few public officials, whom he did not name. 
</P>
<P>
Abraham Spiegel has provided advice to at least one other Los Angeles elected 
official besides Bradley. County Supervisor Mike Antonovich said he purchased 
Columbia stock after it was recommended to him by Abraham Spiegel. 
</P>
<P>
The source close to Bradley said Abraham Spiegel's office served as a conduit 
to the mayor on his investment in Columbia. It is not known if other stocks 
were involved. 
</P>
<P>
The relationship between Abraham Spiegel and Bradley regarding investments is 
among the subjects being reviewed by the mayor's lawyers, said Mark Fabiani, 
Bradley's legal counsel at City Hall. 
</P>
<P>
Asked specifically whether Abraham Spiegel may have passed any investment 
advice onto Bradley, Fabiani said: "That's part of the information being 
assembled." He would not provide any further details about how the lawyers are 
piecing together the mayor's financial transactions. 
</P>
<P>
Columbia spokeswoman Lenore Hatch said Thursday that Abraham Spiegel was out of 
the country and unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'20-Year Relationship' 
</P>
<P>
"Abraham Spiegel has had a 20-year relationship with the mayor," Hatch said. 
"We don't believe that anything inappropriate has been done. Beyond that, we 
can make no comment about the relationship." 
</P>
<P>
Steven Faigen, a Shearson spokesman, said the firm does not comment on its 
customers "out of respect for people's privacy." 
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Los Angeles City Councilman Michael Woo said the council's 
Governmental Operations Committee is considering expanding its review of 
Bradley's financial affairs to include his relations with Drexel. 
</P>
<P>
The committee has already held two sessions dealing with City Atty. James K. 
Hahn's investigation into fees paid to Bradley by Far East National Bank and 
Valley Federal Savings &amp; Loan Assn., both of which had dealings with the 
city. That investigation is expected to last several months. 
</P>
<P>
"The central question in all these matters is: Did the mayor use his capacity 
as mayor to benefit himself personally?" Woo said in an interview. "The 
disclosures about Drexel Burnham relate back to that central question." 
</P>
<P>
Bradley refused Thursday to discuss his investments or the subpoena of his 
records. 
</P>
<P>
"You've known for a long time that I have not taken any questions dealing with 
the inquiries that the city attorney and others are now engaged in," Bradley 
told reporters after a National League of Cities meeting on gang problems. 
"When that's over, I'll be glad to talk about it." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
First Purchase in 1979 
</P>
<P>
Bradley first purchased Columbia Savings stock in 1979 and then obtained more 
stock in the thrift in 1984, according to his financial disclosure forms. In 
1986, he reported that his investment in Columbia exceeded $100,000 in value. 
After the stock market crash of October, 1987, Bradley reported in his most 
recent filings that he owned between $10,000 and $100,000 of Columbia stock. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley reports having a loan of at least $10,000 from Columbia Savings, and 
his longtime special assistant, William Elkins, has reported earning more than 
$10,000 annually in outside income as a Columbia director. Elkins also holds 
between $10,000 and $100,000 in Columbia stock. 
</P>
<P>
The Spiegel family, Columbia and its employees have contributed $53,130 to 
Bradley's political campaigns since 1983, records show. 
</P>
<P>
The mayor and Abraham Spiegel have enjoyed a close personal relationship since 
Bradley was a city councilman in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
Spiegel has been Bradley's "point man" in the Jewish community that is such an 
important part of his political and fund-raising base, said one Democrat, who 
is influential in Westside Jewish politics. 
</P>
<P>
"Abe Spiegel has taken Tom Bradley by the hand to all sorts of Jewish events I 
have been at," the source said. 
</P>
<P>
Spiegel accompanied Bradley on a 1985 trade mission to Jerusalem, where Spiegel 
announced a $1.5-million donation to the Yad Vashem memorial for Jewish 
children killed in the holocaust. Bradley and Spiegel returned to Jerusalem in 
1987 to attend the dedication ceremony of the memorial. 
</P>
<P>
Bradley tentatively planned to join Spiegel on his current trip to Israel but 
backed out "some weeks ago," said Bill Chandler, the mayor's spokesman. 
Chandler said he characterized as mere speculation any suggestion that the 
mayor canceled his trip because of his sudden political troubles. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Plays Pivotal Role 
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Spiegel was among several influential business leaders who played a 
pivotal role in persuading Bradley to reverse his opposition to Occidental 
Petroleum Corp.'s plan to drill for oil off Pacific Palisades. 
</P>
<P>
In Antonovich's case, the advice from Spiegel led the supervisor to purchase 
common stock in Columbia Savings in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
"I asked him for some good investments, and I ended up investing in Columbia," 
Antonovich said. 
</P>
<P>
In 1982, Antonovich named Spiegel, whom he described as a longtime friend, as 
his representative to the county Board of Retirement. 
</P>
<P>
According to his statement of economic interests, Antonovich purchased between 
$10,001 and $100,000 of Columbia Savings &amp; Loan stock on May 31, 1985 and 
acquired more later. 
</P>
<P>
Over the next two years, Antonovich sold his Columbia stock because the trades 
turned out to be "poor long-term investments." 
</P>
<P>
Times staff writers Frank Clifford, Cathleen Decker, Tom Furlong, Victor Merina 
and Dean Murphy contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
May 20, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
The Times reported Friday that Columbia Savings &amp; Loan executive Abraham 
Spiegel was among several influential business leaders who played a pivotal 
role in 1985 in "persuading" Mayor Tom Bradley to reverse his opposition to 
Occidental Petroleum's proposed oil-drilling off Pacific Palisades. The 
assertion oversimplified material in a previous article in The Times, in which 
Spiegel was identified as one of several business leaders who supported the 
Occidental position. Friday's article was not meant to imply that Spiegel spoke 
directly to the mayor on the issue. The mayor said Friday that he made an 
independent judgment on the Occidental plan, and did not discuss it with 
Spiegel or any other business leader. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
