<HEADLINE>
<P>
UAW FILES PETITION FOR ELECTION AT NISSAN'S PLANT IN TENNESEE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SMYRNA, Tenn. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After 16 months of organizing, the United Auto Workers union filed a petition 
Thursday calling for an election at the Nissan automobile and truck plant here. 
</P>
<P>
The filing with the National Labor Relations Board sets up a showdown between 
organized labor and the second-largest Japanese automobile plant in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
Eleven union leaders and workers led by Jim Weaver, who has coordinated the 
drive since January, took a box of cards signed by Nissan employees to the NLRB 
office in Nashville Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
Buddy Shonting, a technician in the trim and chassis plant, said, "I think 
we're going to whip the britches off of them." 
</P>
<P>
Union officials had wanted to time the filing so that the election would occur 
on a favorable day for them either before or after the plant takes its regular 
annual production break July 3-17. 
</P>
<P>
Company officials have said that it would probably take about 60 days after a 
petition is filed for the NLRB to hold an election. 
</P>
<P>
Gail Neuman, vice president of human resources for the company, welcomed a 
conclusion to months of organizing that often left employees bitterly divided. 
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the great majority of Nissan employees will vote against 
the union," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
