<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: STAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and international 
news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Judy Davis, playing the title role in "Hapgood" at the Ahmanson Theatre, was 
forced to leave at the end of the second act Wednesday night because of voice 
problems. She replaced by understudy Babbie Green. Davis earlier had received 
medical treatment for a throat ailment, and thought she was well enough to 
perform, said theatre spokesman Tony Sherwood. "She went on, thought she could 
get through it and lost her voice," he said. She missed Thursday's matinee 
performance, but was expected to be back on stage Thursday night, Sherwood 
said. Davis was the star of the Australian film, "My Brilliant Career." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
May 20, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
Friday's Morning Report misidentified the theater where "Hapgood" is playing. 
Although the play is offered as part of the Ahmanson Theatre season, the 
production is at the Doolittle Theatre in Hollywood. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
