<HEADLINE>
<P>
AUDIOCASSETTE REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
THE ODD CHARACTERS OF 'CADILLAC JACK' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES CHAMPLIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
**** "Cadillac Jack" by Larry McMurtry. Read by Wolfram Kandinsky. Unabridged 
on 10 cassettes. Books on Tape. 
</P>
<P>
Larry McMurtry, author of "Lonesome Dove" and several other novels, is also an 
antiquarian book collector and dealer. The first person narrator of "Cadillac 
Jack" is a scout who makes a (good) living looking into flea markets, auctions 
and obscure shops from one end of the U.S. to the other, buying beautiful 
things for resale to dealers and collectors. He also collects women with rather 
more mixed results. The book is wonderfully satirical about Washington (where 
McMurtry now lives) and Texas (where he hails from) and all points in between. 
"Cadillac Jack" is rich in oddball characters, funny in its dissection of 
relationships, quite touching in the passionate detailing of the scout's love 
of objects rare, beautiful and bizarre, or all three. Kandinsky, who has read 
all of McMurtry's work for the label, has a laconic voice and a subtle command 
of American regional accents that fits the material like a caressing glove. 
Information: (800) 626-3333 CHARLES CHAMPLIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Recording Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051989-0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 59124 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 19, 1989, Friday, Home Edition 
</P>
