</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
236 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE GALLERIES: THE VALLEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUVAN GEER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For artist and gallery owner Phillip Orlando, the way the figure is depicted 
can be telling. He sees in figurative representation something of a cultural 
mask that can simultaneously reinforce certain ideas or hide them from the 
uninitiated. This idea, pretty basic to social archeologists but not often 
discussed in relation to figurative art, forms the premise to his paintings and 
small constructions. 
</P>
<P>
Sadly, the naive, somewhat predictable paintings of African masks and spirit 
effigy don't add much to the notion. Like hero worship content with 
appearances, they seem happy to copy the artifacts in a sort of Dadaesque 
appreciation of the abstract figurative form. Meaning isn't amplified. 
Occasional pieces like "Marka With Shadow" look good and keep the original's 
mysterious aura of spirituality. But even collaged magazine photos can't 
connect the overall symbolism to this culture. 
</P>
<P>
In his trendy magazines turned trashy masks, however, Orlando sets up an 
interesting analysis of figuration-as-symbol in this culture. It's a point of 
view reflecting the harsh glare and hype of media promotion on ideas of 
sexuality and success. Not incidentally, the glitzy magazines make strangely 
empty masks. Fascinating yet repellent, they pointedly turn Orlando's cutting, 
collaging and painting into something part exorcism, part adolescent fan club. 
(Orlando Gallery, 14553 Ventura Blvd., to May 26.).SUVAN GEER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Art Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051989-0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 59132 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 19, 1989, Friday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part 6; Page 22; Column 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1087 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MAKING MUSIC IS A POWERFUL EXPERIENCE FOR THE SAN FERNANDO VALLEY CHORALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRISTINE ZIAYA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Margaret and Bob Rouse, both 67, have been married for 43 years. They met 
nearly half a century ago at Colorado Springs High School. Margaret had the 
lead role in Gilbert and Sullivan's "H.M.S. Pinafore." Bob was a string bass 
player in the orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
They loved music then -- and still do. 
</P>
<P>
"Our music is a strong bond," Margaret said. And as members of the San Fernando 
Valley Chorale, the Van Nuys couple eagerly attend choral rehearsals each week 
at Our Saviour's Lutheran Church in Granada Hills. 
</P>
<P>
"When spouses go out separately, there can be a degree of resentment," Bob 
said. "But we go out to rehearsals together. It brings us closer." 
</P>
<P>
Every Tuesday evening, the Rouses blend their voices with about 30 other 
Chorale singers. Their repertoire includes a variety of music -- classical, 
liturgical, comedy, folk, motion picture themes, and of course, those 
ever-popular Broadway hits. 
</P>
<P>
The Rouses agree that the Chorale brings them a sense of accomplishment, 
relaxation and pleasure. Making music is fun. 
</P>
<P>
Since 1974, the Chorale has provided the opportunity for such qualities to 
dozens of non-professionals -- singers of all ages and from all walks of life. 
Started by John Ellis, who also founded the Burbank Civic Light Opera in 1950, 
the Chorale has, over the years, made appearances throughout the Valley and Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
There have been performances at convalescent homes, hospitals, meetings of 
civic organizations, churches and shopping malls. The group also has performed 
on a couple of occasions at the Music Center of the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion 
and has regularly appeared at the Hall of Liberty in Forest Lawn with the Los 
Angeles Solo Repertory Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
The Chorale has also performed with the Highland Park Symphony Orchestra and 
the Korean Philharmonic Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
For Chorale members like Carl Frain, 63, who served as the group's first 
president, it is the thrill of performing that keeps him coming back year after 
year. 
</P>
<P>
"When I was young, I thought I might be a Big Band singer -- me and everyone 
else," Frain reminisced. "In high school, I sang and acted. I've been singing 
all my life. There's nothing better to do than sing." 
</P>
<P>
On occasion, Frain did sing professionally, but his chief occupation was as a 
machinist. 
</P>
<P>
When he suffered two strokes two years ago, getting back to the Chorale served 
as a powerful incentive to recover. "I was singing within three or four 
months," he said. "When I got back into singing, it was good exercise. Like 
sports, your muscles build up. As soon as I got back, it helped me vocally." 
</P>
<P>
Joining the Chorale is relatively painless, said President Ron Blair. 
Interested vocalists simply show up at one of the rehearsals and start singing 
with the group. 
</P>
<P>
After three rehearsals, the prospective member can meet with the director, who 
has the power to accept the newcomer or not. More often than not, he or she is 
welcomed. 
</P>
<P>
Over the years, a few people have been turned away, however. And some have been 
accepted who dropped out later. Blair remembers one man who had difficulty 
blending with the group. "He sang like he was in a bar," Blair recalled, 
laughing. "Eventually, he did quit." 
</P>
<P>
Besides attending weekly rehearsals, participants are required to meet a 
performance dress code and pay yearly dues of $50, which are used to offset the 
group's expenses, including payments to the Chorale's director and accompanist. 
</P>
<P>
Although joining is simple, in recent years, keeping the nonprofit group alive 
has been a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
A major difficulty has been finances. When the Chorale was started in 1974, it 
was sponsored by Los Angeles' Bureau of Music and received municipal funding. 
However, in July, 1986, the Los Angeles Cultural Affairs Department cut off the 
city's assistance. This resulted in a crunch for the Chorale, since its annual 
operating budget is between $4,000 and $6,000. 
</P>
<P>
To make ends meet, the group raises funds with regularly scheduled concerts and 
occasional special fund-raisers, and solicits donations from friends. Last 
summer they held a garage sale. 
</P>
<P>
"We're running on a shoestring," Blair said. They are actively seeking a 
sponsor, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Besides the financial problems, the Chorale recently faced another obstacle. In 
December, 1987, Robert Mantzke, the Chorale's popular director since 1984, died 
of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
To keep things running smoothly, the Chorale's board appointed member Margaret 
Blair interim director -- a move that made some members unhappy. "Maybe they 
weren't comfortable having a woman as a director," Ron Blair (no relation) 
said, "even though she was qualified." 
</P>
<P>
A division within the group ensued. In January, 1988, about 20 members decided 
to leave the Chorale to start a separate singing group. 
</P>
<P>
The schism added to the already low spirits of the Chorale. Yet, determined to 
prevail, in July, 1988, they selected Conrad Immel as a new director, and a new 
era began. 
</P>
<P>
As a Fulbright scholar, Immel had studied in Vienna and Italy before launching 
an eight-year operatic career in Germany and Austria. He has a master's degree 
in music literature and a bachelor's degree in voice from the University of 
Texas in Austin, and was an assistant professor of vocal arts at the USC for 
four years. 
</P>
<P>
Immel says that his standards are high, but that members of the Chorale share 
his enthusiasm for quality work. "My philosophy is that anything worth doing is 
worth doing well," he said. "With an amateur group, it just takes a little 
longer. Excellence in this type of situation is something worth striving for." 
</P>
<P>
Unlike former directors, Immel dedicates part of each rehearsal session to 
actually teaching vocal techniques. But it's not all hard work, he said. "I try 
to be funny," he said with a chuckle. 
</P>
<P>
More important, he views the group as an outlet for creative expression and 
values its continued existence. "With TV and records, it is really easy to slip 
into the mode of letting other people make music," Immel said. "The Chorale 
provides members with the opportunity to sing great music from their heart and 
soul. It's an opportunity to project their emotion, and when they perform, to 
move other people, too. They are able to create a real special sense with the 
audience." 
</P>
<P>
 The San Fernando Valley Chorale presents two major concerts each year. On May 
21, it will perform at 3 p.m. at Our Saviour's Lutheran Church, 16603 San 
Fernando Mission Blvd., Granada Hills. Admission is by donation. For additional 
information about the Chorale, call (818) 891-2922. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, From left, Chorale members Nathaniel Brodsky, Doug Sutherland, Bob 
Rouse, Carl Frain and (barely visible) Lee Ford rehearse. CARLOS CHAVEZ / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
