<P>
Thousands of protesters demonstrated in 11 South Korean cities on the 
anniversary of the 1980 uprising in the southwestern city of Kwangju, burning 
effigies of President Roh Tae Woo and calling for the withdrawal of U.S. troops 
from the country. In Kwangju, an estimated 100,000 people rallied, while in 
Seoul and other cities, thousands joined marches, protests and religious 
services. The 10-day Kwangju uprising, which killed nearly 200 people by 
official count, hundreds more by unofficial reports, occurred after Roh's 
predecessor, Chun Doo Hwan, declared martial law and jailed opposition leaders. 
