<HEADLINE>
<P>
VOTE ON SANTA MARGARITA DELAYED; 
</P>
<P>
DECISION TO INCLUDE SCHOOL IN PUBLIC LEAGUE POSTPONED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE LOWERY, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Santa Margarita High School, which appeared to have taken a step toward finding 
a public league to call home last week, was pushed back a step Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
The Southern Section's executive committee decided to delay a vote on whether 
to include the school in the Orange County geographical area after county 
principals and superintendents complained that they were not properly informed 
about the situation. 
</P>
<P>
"It looks like we're back at square one," said Santa Margarita principal Father 
Michael Harris, whose school will remain in the Olympic League through the 
1989-90 school year. 
</P>
<P>
Santa Margarita, a two-year-old Catholic high school in south Orange County, 
asked to be placed in the Orange County region, which would mean its inclusion 
in a public school league, most likely the Pacific Coast, South Coast, Sea View 
or Sunset. 
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, it appeared to have its wish when Orange County league 
representatives voted to recommend to the section's executive committee that 
Santa Margarita be included in the Orange County area for the 1990-92 
releaguing years. 
</P>
<P>
But after the vote, some high school principals and district superintendents 
complained to the Southern Section that league officials had not communicated 
or met with them before it. 
</P>
<P>
"I thought we had a meeting of the minds," said Stan Thomas, Southern Section 
commissioner. "But apparently some of the league representatives did not 
communicate well with their principals." 
</P>
<P>
Robert Packer, an executive committee member and superintendent of the Duarte 
Unified School District, chided league representatives during the meeting for 
not communicating with their principals. 
</P>
<P>
The executive committee will meet June 7 at the Southern Section office in 
Cerritos to vote on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
Thomas will meet with Orange County principals and superintendents today at 
Foothill High School to answer questions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
