<HEADLINE>
<P>
BREEDING BIRDS: RED-TAILED HAWK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Clipboard researched by Susan Davis Greene and Rick VanderKnyff / Los 
Angeles Times: Graphics by Doris Shields / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RED-TAILED HAWK 
</P>
<P>
(Buteo jamaicensis) 
</P>
<P>
Description: About 22 inches long, with a 50-inch wingspan. Wings are broad and 
fairly rounded, plumage is variable. Reddish upper-tail, paler red under-tail; 
pale mottling on shoulders, 
</P>
<P>
contrasting with dark mantle and often forming a "V" in perched birds. 
</P>
<P>
Habitat: Woodland and open country with scattered trees; often seen perching on 
light poles. 
</P>
<P>
Diet: More than 85% rodents; also amphibians, crayfish, fish and refuse. 
</P>
<P>
Displays: Aerial display: pair spiral, recross, male usually circling behind 
and above female. 
</P>
<P>
Nest: Bulky nest of sticks and twigs built in crotch of large tree with 
commanding view. Alternately uses several perennial nests. 
</P>
<P>
Eggs: White to bluish white, spotted with brown or unmarked; about 2 1/2 inches 
long. 
</P>
<P>
Natural history notes: The most common and widespread of the buteos 
(high-soaring hawks that are among the easiest daytime birds of prey to spot). 
While it shuns the deepest woodlands and most heavily-urbanized areas, it is a 
common suburban bird in the county. In addition to the local breeders, many 
migrating red-tails visit the county in spring and fall. 
</P>
<P>
Breeding bird atlas: To report bird breeding activity in your neighborhood, or 
to get information on the breeding bird atlas (now in its fifth and final 
year), call Sea and Sage Audubon Society members Sylvia Gallagher, (714) 
962-8990, or Nancy Kenyon, (714) 786-3160. 
</P>
<P>
Note: Map is divided into 5-kilometer squares so that Audubon Society 
volunteers can more easily survey areas on a regular basis. 
</P>
<P>
Sources: Sea and Sage Audubon Society; "The Birder's Handbook," Ehrlich, Dobkin 
and Wheye, Fireside Books (1988); "Field Guide to the Birds of North America," 
National Geographic Society (1987); "Birds of Southern California: Status and 
Distribution," Garrett and Dunn, Los Angeles Audubon Society (1981). 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Map, breeding areas, RUSS ARASMITH / Los Angeles Times ; Drawing, RED-TAILED 
HAWK, RUSS ARASMITH / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
