</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATURAL POET; 
</P>
<P>
IRVINE ARTIST'S WORKS OFTEN REFLECT QUEST FOR HER PLACE IN AMERICAN CULTURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PENELOPE MOFFET, Penelope Moffet is a free-lance writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Every day, Irvine poet Mitsuye Yamada rises before dawn to write. It's that 
quiet time that poet Sylvia Plath called the "blue hour." 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody calls me up at 4:30 in the morning," Yamada said. "I have a body of 
time. I have a journal I keep with fragments of thought, and I try to put them 
into a poem." 
</P>
<P>
Many of her poems reflect her efforts to find her place in American culture. 
Yamada, who was born in Japan and raised in the United States, sees herself as 
part of a movement of Asian-American writers exploring their heritage. 
</P>
<P>
Long active within the Orange County literary community, Yamada, 65, recently 
published her second book, "Desert Run." She'll read from the book at the 
Fullerton Museum Center on Saturday at 8 p.m., along with Janet Jue and Sarie 
Sachie Hylkema, as part of a poets reading series. 
</P>
<P>
"Desert Run," published in late 1988 by Kitchen Table: Women of Color Press of 
Latham, N.Y., has won praise from critics such as Scarlet Cheng, who wrote in 
the Arlington, Va.-based Belles Lettres magazine that "Yamada's poetry has a 
terse blend of emotions and imagery: the twist of words that creates the twist 
of vision that makes poetry alive for us." 
</P>
<P>
Poet Eloise Klein Healy, coordinator of the Cal State Northridge women's 
studies interdisciplinary program, says she's "impressed by the kind of dignity 
that (Yamada) brings to everything. She has such an open vision of the world." 
</P>
<P>
Yamada's progress as a writer in the years between her first book of poetry, 
"Camp Notes and Other Poems" (1976, Shameless Hussy Press, Berkeley), and 
"Desert Run" is considerable, Healy said. "The technical growth in these poems 
is amazing." 
</P>
<P>
In addition to her books, Yamada has published work in a number of literary 
magazines and anthologies, including the 1989 Norton anthology of 
cross-cultural writing, "New Worlds of Literature." In 1981 she was featured, 
along with Bay Area writer Nellie Wong, in a film, "Mitsuye and Nellie: Two 
American Poets," that aired nationally on PBS. 
</P>
<P>
Yamada was one of the editors for a 1986 anthology of Orange County poets, "The 
Webs We Weave," and in 1981 founded a group called the Multi-Cultural Women 
Writers of Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
Her poems are narratives written in free verse. "You have to make your own way 
into finding your own form," she said. "I don't know if I've found mine." 
</P>
<P>
A recently retired Cypress College professor of English, Yamada has lived in 
Irvine for 17 years with her husband of 39 years, Yoshikazu Yamada, a retired 
research chemist who recently became the proprietor of a Laguna Beach art 
gallery. They have four children and three grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
Yamada said her teaching helped pay the family's bills while leaving her some 
time to write, though the full-time job contributed to the long lapse between 
her first and second book. It's very difficult -- if not impossible -- to earn 
a living as a poet today, she noted. 
</P>
<P>
"The books themselves don't seem to sell very well. We live in a society where 
not very many people sit down and read poetry," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Given the limited readership for poetry, she's not sure why she goes on writing 
it, Yamada said. Yet, she added, "if we want to survive as human beings, be 
aware of our place in the world, you might say that (writing and reading) 
poetry is a matter of survival." 
</P>
<P>
Yamada was born in Kyushu, Japan, and raised in Seattle. She began writing at 
age 13, but became more serious about it much later, in the mid-1960s. "There 
was a period when I was sick. I was in bed a lot," Yamada said. "That was when 
I really started writing a lot. I wanted my children to know about my life." 
</P>
<P>
She was misdiagnosed first as having terminal emphysema, then cystic fibrosis. 
"I didn't sleep much at all, my lungs were in such bad shape. I did a lot of 
writing and thinking about things." Later, the diagnosis was changed to asthma, 
which medication brought under control. Yamada discarded much of what she'd 
written while sick but went on putting her thoughts on paper. 
</P>
<P>
"In the 1970s, when various feminist publications started coming out, I started 
sending my things out," Yamada said. Poems were accepted. "That was exciting, 
an affirmation." 
</P>
<P>
Yamada's father, Jack Yasutake, was also a poet. When she was a girl, Yamada 
remembers, every Sunday he met with a large group of poets in Seattle. "In 
fact, that's what they were doing on Dec. 7," 1941, the day Pearl Harbor was 
attacked by the Japanese, Yamada said. "That's where they were when my father 
was arrested." 
</P>
<P>
The writers had inscribed poems on a big piece of paper on a wall. FBI agents 
removed the paper. "They thought it was some sort of code. They took it away to 
see if some kind of subversive activity was going on that day," Yamada said. 
Yasutake was incarcerated in prisoner-of-war camps near Albuquerque, N.M., and 
Crystal City, Tex., for most of the war. 
</P>
<P>
Like many other Japanese Americans, Yamada, her mother and brothers were 
interned. Yamada was held from 1942 to 1943 at Minidoka, an Idaho camp. Once 
released, she was at first eager to leave her camp memories behind, but later 
these memories became the subject of much of her writing. 
</P>
<P>
In her new book's title poem Yamada likens herself, and other interned 
Japanese-Americans, to "the bull snakes brought/into this desert by the 
soldiers/we were transported here/to drive away rattlers/in your nightmares. . 
. ." 
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the poem, still using the image of the bull snake as a metaphor 
for herself, Yamada writes that "I cannot stay in the desert/where you will 
have me nor/will I be brought back in a cage/to grace your need for exotica. . 
. . If you must fit me to your needs/I will die/and so will you." The "you" to 
whom she speaks in the poem is the culture that allowed the internment of 
Japanese-Americans, she says. 
</P>
<P>
"The American guilt about the camps is to keep it quiet. That's why it took 40 
years for this redress issue to come out," she said. "Even in the Japanese 
community, the fear is that there might be a backlash. But as (poet) Audre Lord 
said, 'My silence did not protect me and your silence will not protect you.' 
</P>
<P>
"I don't know how many thousands of people still don't know what this (redress) 
is about," said Yamada, who was active with the National Council of 
Japanese-American Redress, which brought an unsuccessful class-action lawsuit 
on behalf of those interned during World War II. (Recent federal legislation 
mandated that World War II Japanese-American internees be paid $20,000 each as 
redress, but those payments have not yet begun.) 
</P>
<P>
Although Yamada was born in Japan, she doesn't feel Japanese. In 1981 she paid 
her first adult visit to her birthplace, and "I knew that this was not my 
country," she said. Brought to the United States at age 4, Yamada had spent 
another 18 months in Japan when she was 11, but she hadn't been back since. 
</P>
<P>
"My heritage is really with the pioneers, no matter what race. I feel more 
connected to the emigres from throughout the world who move from one culture to 
another and spend the rest of their lives trying to wedge themselves into this 
new culture," Yamada said. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. laws discriminating against people of Asian origin prevented Yamada from 
becoming an American citizen until 1953. "I was unnatural before, so I had to 
become naturalized," she joked. "That term is so . . ." She left the sentence 
unfinished, shaking her head. "But by then I was already more American than 
Japanese." 
</P>
<P>
Partly because of her personal encounters with injustice, Yamada feels a strong 
kinship with political prisoners around the world. She's been a member of 
Amnesty International, the human rights organization, for more than 20 years 
and is up for reelection to its national board of directors. 
</P>
<P>
Through her teaching, Yamada presented her students with alternative traditions 
within American literature. In her American literature class, for instance, the 
reading list was mostly books by ethnic American writers. 
</P>
<P>
"The students would complain that there were too many ethnic novels. They'd 
want to know why they weren't reading Hemingway, and I'd explain there were 
many years when we read nothing but white male writers," Yamada said. 
</P>
<P>
"Students are so conformist. . . . We didn't throw all the mainstream people 
out. I kept some of the women" writers, she added, laughing. 
</P>
<P>
Yamada continues to be an active member of Multi-Cultural Women Writers of 
Orange County. "We started out as an Asian-American women writers group," she 
said. However, the membership soon expanded to include several other "women 
with a very strong ethnic consciousness." Nine women now meet every other week 
to share their writing. 
</P>
<P>
In 1988 the group won a 3-year grant of $2,000 a year from the California Arts 
Council to present a few seminars and to publish a multilingual anthology of 
members' writing, due out next year. 
</P>
<P>
Yamada's current writing, which includes a book of political essays for 
Firebrand Press, is going slowly. She said her life "feels very disordered 
right now" because she's trying to do so many things. 
</P>
<P>
One of her projects involves trying to find out why her father was considered a 
dangerous spy during World War II. "The paper trail takes forever. . . . I 
should have retired 10 years ago to work on some of these things," Yamada said. 
</P>
<P>
She's happy to have more time to pursue interests close to her heart. "I think 
I deserve it," she said. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Excerpts From 'Desert Run' 
</P>
<P>
Following is an excerpt from Mitsuye Yamada's book, "Desert Run." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
MY COUSIN 
</P>
<P>
 The failed kamikaze pilot 
</P>
<P>
 who lived to miss only three fingers 
</P>
<P>
 on his right hand 
</P>
<P>
 offers me a sip of California wine 
</P>
<P>
 in his trim garden. 
</P>
<P>
 He, pacific, a giant 
</P>
<P>
 among dwarfed trees 
</P>
<P>
 one hand resting 
</P>
<P>
 on the arm of 
</P>
<P>
 an imported chair 
</P>
<P>
 a clear stemmed glass poised 
</P>
<P>
 between his thumb and pinkie 
</P>
<P>
 answers a question I could not 
</P>
<P>
 ask for thirty years: 
</P>
<P>
 Of course I don't 
</P>
<P>
 I don't really believe 
</P>
<P>
 "it is sweet and fitting 
</P>
<P>
 to die for one's country." 
</P>
<P>
 It is evening and the canary clears its throat. 
</P>
<P>
 I leave among cricket sounds in the woods. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
